WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Great, so I'm Kristin and today I'm going to be talking about automating for consistency.

00:00:05.000 --> 00:00:10.000
So, my first opinion for you is perhaps a little bit controversial.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
So, your data may never be standardized.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
But, you can still build consistent processes and products,

00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:20.000
and automation is a tool that you can use to help.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:24.000
And so, in this talk I'm going to be talking about how we built a custom R package

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:26.000
to handle our disparate data sources,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
to deliver consistent reports for our downstream users,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.000
and how we used automation to kind of enable user adoption.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.000
And I hope that you can kind of take away some ideas from this talk

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.000
and bring them back to your own work.

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
So, why do we care about consistent data?

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:45.000
So, consistent data is really valuable data.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
It's how we get data in the hands of people quicker,

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and it can lead to faster decision making, and also better decision making.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And I work in the pharma industry.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
So, I work in the pharma industry, and so we work with patient data.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:05.000
And so, every data point we work with is a sample that's been provided by a patient.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
And so, it's really important to remember that the patients are giving us

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.000
a lot of information from this data,

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:13.000
and that we really need to use every data point we can.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
And the patients are hoping that this can help them with their treatments,

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
but moreover can help the future generation,

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:24.000
so that patients with the same cancer as them in the future can have better outcomes.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.000
And so, slowdowns in our process really mean that medicines aren't being delivered

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
to patients as quickly as they can.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000
So, we need to really move fast in our process.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
So, I'll give you a little bit more context in the specific data that we work with.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:40.000
So, we work with the clinical biomarker data,

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
and I'm part of the translational oncology group at Pfizer in the bioinformatics group.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
And so, what this means is we're working with the biomarker data

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:52.000
that comes out of clinical trials, and we're really trying to assess

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
how patients are responding to their treatments.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
And so, my group supports over 45 different oncology trials.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And throughout these trials, patients will be providing samples.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
So, this might be a blood sample they provide when they're seeing their doctor.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
It could be a biopsy.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And then, these samples are tested for things called biomarkers.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:14.000
And so, a biomarker is just a readout of biological activity.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
So, an example of one might be a DNA mutation

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:21.000
that's indicating that there's cancer in the body.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:24.000
And so, these samples are usually collected at the hospitals

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:26.000
and then sent to external vendors.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
And the external vendors are actually going to be doing the testing.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
And then, they'll take the data and send that back to us.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And we work with a lot of vendors, so over 20 vendors.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
And that means that we're receiving data in different formats

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:39.000
from these different vendors.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
And it's also important to note that biomarker data

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
is a little bit less standardized than other clinical data.

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
So, some of the data is actually entered into spreadsheets manually

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.000
by scientists at these external labs.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And so, it's really important that we assess this data for quality.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
So, I wanted to give you an example of what some of our data might look like

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
and what types of quality control we're performing on the data.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
So, this is data from a single patient and a single biopsy.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And so, what we're really trying to assess is,

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:14.000
did we receive the data we were expecting to receive?

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
Is it in the correct format?

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:20.000
And did the tests get performed in the way it was supposed to get performed?

00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:24.000
So, some of the things we might look at is just to see, like,

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
the person who was performing this test,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:28.000
did they think they could actually evaluate it?

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:30.000
Was it acceptable?

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And so, we're looking for these values to say yes.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
Other things we might see in the data set are percentages.

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:37.000
And so, we want to make sure these are all numbers.

00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
They're between 0 and 100.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
And then, there's a few things we might actually do

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
that are calculations between different values in our data.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:47.000
So, some of the tests are really sensitive.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
They need to get tested right away when the vendor receives them.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And so, we might do some calculations on these dates that we received

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
just to make sure it was done quickly.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
And so, you might say, this type of QC looks pretty straightforward.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:02.000
But when I joined the team four years ago,

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
our QC was taking a lot of time.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
It was very time-consuming.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
And this is because we had inconsistent data structures

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:13.000
that really required manual coding and review for each data set.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:16.000
We had another group of colleagues that actually didn't have any programmatic support.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
And they were doing this all manually by eye.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:21.000
And it took hours every month.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:23.000
And it's not too bad when you're working on one data set.

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
But when you have dozens of studies and dozens of data sets,

00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:27.000
it really adds up.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:31.000
And it also means that our data is not handled consistently between our trials.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And it's really difficult to track what was done.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
So, the issue that we're facing is not that our data has issues in it.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
That's expected.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
But that we have inconsistency between our different data sets.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
And that's really preventing us from scaling the process.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:49.000
And we need to scale the process

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
in order to handle the volume of data sets that we're working with.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
So, when we're talking about consistency,

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
what exactly are we talking about?

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:01.000
What types of consistency do we need

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
in order to scale and automate our process?

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
So, it turns out, actually, a lot of different areas.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So, we need our data to be in the same location

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
and to be accessible at all the times.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
We need our data to be defined

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:16.000
so we can find the specific information that we're looking for

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
where we need to find it.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
We need our data to be internally consistent.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
So, when we receive data files,

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:25.000
it's not changing too much from one file to the next file.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
We also need to be consistent in terms of what we do to the data.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
So, if we are performing any transformations or processing on the data,

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
it needs to be consistent between our studies.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:39.000
And then, if something was to change throughout the process,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:41.000
we need to be able to consistently track that

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:43.000
so we can see what we're doing.

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:45.000
And then, lastly, once we find issues,

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:47.000
we need to generate consistent reports

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:50.000
so that our downstream users can find what they need to find

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:52.000
so they can act on the data.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.000
So, when we started designing our system,

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
we realized we really needed an adaptable solution

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
that could handle the complexity in our data,

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:05.000
but also one that would facilitate standardization and automation.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
And so, I wanted to kind of compare two different processes

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:11.000
or two different approaches that we could take.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:12.000
So, we could take a single process

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
that's just one process that would be applied

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
to all of our different datasets,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
or we could use a set of one-off processes

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
that were kind of fit for purpose.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And so, both of them have advantages.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
If we look at the single process,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:27.000
we can see it's going to be very standard

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:29.000
and consistent and reproducible.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:30.000
And it's going to apply the same code

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:32.000
exactly the same way to all our datasets.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:34.000
And that is really great.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:36.000
But we'll run into a few challenging edge cases

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:39.000
that really strain the ability of the system

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:42.000
to be able to handle all of the distinct datasets.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.000
So, then we start kind of looking a little bit

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:46.000
at the other end of the spectrum,

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
where the flexible, adaptable, fit-for-purpose system

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
really starts to look more appealing.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:52.000
And it's really kind of a balance between these

00:06:52.000 --> 00:06:54.000
that we realized we needed.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
So, we worked on a solution.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:06:59.000
It's a custom R package that we wrote.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:02.000
It's called WrangleIt to handle our data wrangling.

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:05.000
And it takes advantages of both of these systems.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:07.000
So, it is a single unified process,

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:10.000
but it integrates multiple bespoke components

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
that allow us to bring study-level specifics

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
into our process.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
So, this slide is just kind of an overview

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
of what our package does.

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:21.000
So, it will do some light data transformations.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.000
It also pivots data if that's needed.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
It detects duplicates,

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
and it also applies our QC rules.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
It saves the output files,

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:34.000
and then it also logs what it's doing.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
And there's a lot of areas

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:39.000
in which we kind of enable flexibility

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
into our uniform package.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
And so, these are in these three areas,

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
where we're transforming data, pivoting data,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:47.000
and detecting duplicates.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:49.000
We really need to know the specifics of the datasets

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:52.000
in order to do those steps.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And we have another step

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
in which we're able to kind of take in

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:57.000
external user input.

00:07:57.000 --> 00:07:58.000
So, we have another group

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:00.000
that is a non-coding group

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:01.000
that's really instrumental

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
in determining what qualifies as quality

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
and what means the data can pass along to analysis.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
And so, this is where we can kind of

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
integrate that input.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
So, kind of how do we do that?

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:18.000
So, we use specification files

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
to kind of bring these study-level specifics

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
into our common framework.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And so, these files are really just providing context.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.000
So, specifics to the dataset that we want to bring in.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:30.000
These could be CSVs, they could be TSVs,

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:31.000
they could be YAML files.

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
Sometimes we use all of three.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:36.000
And they're intended both for humans to use,

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
as well as machines to use.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
And they're really just more transparent

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:41.000
than hard-coded solutions.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
So, it's a lot easier to find information

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:44.000
you're looking for in a CSV

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
than it is in an R script

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
that's maybe 600 lines of code.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
And they're also really easy to edit.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
So, as things change throughout the study,

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
which they do, we can go in and edit them

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:56.000
and then also track what we've changed.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And then, we work with a lot of documents

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
that are kind of defining our structure

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:05.000
that aren't necessarily consistent upstream.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
And so, by pulling them into our own specifications,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:10.000
we can apply our standard code to them

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
and ensure that we have consistency.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
So, we work with three different types

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.000
of specification files.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So, we have a set of files that define

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:21.000
what's in the data itself.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:22.000
What does it mean?

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
How is it organized?

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:25.000
Et cetera.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.000
We have another set of files

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
that defines the QC criteria.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
So, what do we need to check

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
to make sure that we can pass the data along

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:33.000
for analysis?

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:35.000
And then, also another file

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.000
that's related to automation.

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:42.000
So, even though our files really vary

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
in terms of what information they're containing,

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
they have the same components

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:47.000
in each of the files.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
So, each file is going to have information

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:51.000
related to the subject or the patient

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:52.000
on the clinical trial,

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:54.000
the encounter or visit when they go in

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:55.000
and see their provider,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
the samples, if they provided a blood sample

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:58.000
or a biopsy,

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.000
the test instance,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
so maybe this was just tested once,

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.000
maybe it was tested again.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
There'll be that information in the data set.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
And then, also the results

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
or the measurements

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
that were actually assessed.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And so, we use a specification file

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
called the data structure file

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
to really make these associations

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:18.000
between the common components

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:21.000
and the data set specifics really explicit.

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.000
So, in blue we can see

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:26.000
we have the five different components laid out

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:27.000
and then in green

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
we have the data set specific values

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:30.000
that we can really just slide

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:33.000
into these components.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:37.000
And then, I wanted to talk about

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
another data set specification file

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:40.000
as really an example

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.000
of how we're kind of bringing

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
our study level specifics

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
into our common framework.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
And so, this is a data format table.

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
This is a table that's generated by non-coders.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.000
And so, even though it's fairly consistent,

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
our data columns might change,

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
sometimes information will be in the wrong cell

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:58.000
and sometimes it's just actually not correct.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:10:59.000
And so, we need to actually

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.000
pull out this information

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
into our own specification file.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:04.000
And so, we use a Python script

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:06.000
to extract this information out of the table

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:08.000
and then we also use, you know,

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:10.000
human eyes to make sure it's correct.

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:12.000
And kind of as we're going through this,

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:13.000
we'll take the opportunity to see

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:16.000
is there anything that needs to be converted.

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So, we might see we have a date format.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:19.000
We should make sure we're converting that

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
into a date object.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
And we do that through the use of this file.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And it just provides a really nice record

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:28.000
of things that we've changed.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:31.000
And then, the last specification file

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:32.000
that I wanted to go through

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
is our QC rules file.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:37.000
And so, this file contains the ID

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
which will be the name of the rule

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:40.000
that we're using.

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
It will contain the expression.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So, this is the actual R code

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
that is getting run on the data

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
and a human readable description.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:48.000
And it's really nice to have

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:50.000
these three all really linked together.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.000
And we save this in GitHub.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
So, we have a very good source record

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
of what we're doing to the data.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:58.000
And then, if I wanted to compare it,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
the second table is what our output looks like.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
And so, you can also track

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
if you have something like this HER2

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
which is shown up in purple here.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:08.000
You can actually track

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:10.000
what is this rule doing?

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:12.000
What is the actual code that was getting run?

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:14.000
And what is the description?

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.000
And so, this is really nice

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:16.000
for both our programmers

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
as well as our non-coders

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.000
to really be able to see what this is doing.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:22.000
And if we look at this

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:25.000
in terms of a lens of standardization and flexibility,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:28.000
we have both actually in our outputs as well.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:29.000
So, we have flexibility

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
in terms of we're going to report all of the data.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:33.000
And the data is gonna be a little flexible

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
in terms of what's in each file.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:37.000
But we have common components as well.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:40.000
So, all of our outputs have a consistent location

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
where we have the rules that have failed

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
and then also if there's any duplicates that were detected.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And so, it makes it really easier

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
for our downstream users

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:52.000
to find the information that they need to find.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
And so, this is a coding conference.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:55.000
So, I wanted to show you

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:56.000
what some of our code looks like.

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
This is kind of the most basic script

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
and this is what you would need to do

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
in order to initialize your repo,

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
read in your data,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
apply your specification files,

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.000
run all your functions

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
that are gonna generate the outputs,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
and then save the outputs.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
And so, it is just 10 lines of code.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
It's designed to be really simple.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:17.000
It does get more complicated,

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:18.000
but at the heart of it,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:21.000
this is what we're trying to do on each of our data sets.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And specifically, I wanted to call out

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
that it is intentional

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
that we run pretty much all our functions

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.000
from one line of code

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:28.000
so we can really ensure

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
that the code that's being run

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:31.000
is the same on all the data sets.

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And we really restrict the specifics

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
to our specification files.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And we are automating this.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
And so, there's a few considerations

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:42.000
we need to take into account

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:43.000
when we're automating.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
So, all of our code and our specification files

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
are stored in GitHub repositories.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:49.000
And that really allows us

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:53.000
to run in the cloud on an automated schedule.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:56.000
And because we're running it on an automated schedule,

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:59.000
we have no interactive input from users

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:00.000
during our processing.

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:01.000
And so, this means

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
everything needs to be pre-specified.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
So, if you wanted to, say,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
maybe find a new file,

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
a new instance of data that's come in,

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.000
your script is going to have to be able

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:10.000
to do that on its own

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
without any input from you.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
And so, that kind of leads us to system adoption.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:19.000
So, so far, we've been talking about

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
kind of how do we build a system

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
that's able to handle disparate data sources

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:24.000
using the same code.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
But now, how do we get people to use it?

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:29.000
So, my first suggestion

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
is to use code as much as possible.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So, people are really bad at doing the same thing

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
the same way over and over again.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
So, if you can use code to do things

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.000
like name your files,

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
add timestamps, add git hashes,

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:42.000
create your directories,

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
create repos with your pre-existing templates

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:46.000
so you don't need to remember

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
what goes into each file,

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
you can just use a template.

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:50.000
Also, log what your program did

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
and kind of when it performed these actions.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:53.000
So, it's going to get you most of the way

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:54.000
to where you need to be

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
in order to automate your system.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
And then kind of the flip side of that coin

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:02.000
is really limit how much of your system

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:05.000
relies on human interaction.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
So, these parts really add complexity

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
and will inevitably break.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:10.000
So, we have a downstream user group

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
who likes to add comments to our files.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
As we get new data files in,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
it will take their comments and pull them over.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.000
And the system will definitely break.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:21.000
People like to rename columns,

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:23.000
add columns, delete columns, rename files.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
They have done all of these

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
and they did all break our system.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:29.000
So, it does take a little bit of troubleshooting

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:32.000
when you have humans kind of in the loop there.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.000
And then another way in which we kind of

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
enhance system adoption

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
is by making our users' lives easier.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
So, by delivering consistent reports,

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:46.000
we're really allowing people to work independently

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:49.000
and find the information they need for themselves.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
Also, if we anticipate what information they might want,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
we further allow them to kind of work on their own.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
So, they don't need to come back

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
and ask us for questions all the time.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
And then if they're able to find information for themselves,

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:04.000
we're really able to deliver data faster.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
And when people get access to data faster,

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:08.000
usually they're quite excited

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
and that really allows them to kind of

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
enthusiastically take up your system.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
So, if you're able to kind of remove the bottlenecks

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
in which maybe they have to realize they need a report,

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:18.000
they have to email you,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:20.000
you have to find a window to run something,

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:23.000
and then you have to run it,

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
it's really much faster to do it in the background

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
in an automated way.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:30.000
And then you can really deliver more in the order of hours

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:32.000
rather than months.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
And so, kind of as I reach the end of the talk,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
I wanted to reflect again on how automation specifically

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:42.000
enabled us to get to consistency.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:44.000
And so, by thinking about automation,

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:46.000
we had to really ensure that our data storage

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
was in the same spot at the same time

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
and always consistently accessible.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
And we had to also really think about

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
how do we want to bring in our study level specifics

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:56.000
into our common framework.

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
And once we had those in place,

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:00.000
we were able to take the same code

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
and apply it to our distinct data sets.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:06.000
And so, we were able to kind of start scaling our process.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And as we scaled our process,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:09.000
we got to clean data faster.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And as you get to clean data faster,

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:12.000
you enhance user adoption,

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
and then as more users use your system,

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
more data sets get brought into the system,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.000
and then you have more consistency

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
and ultimately result in more valuable data.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:24.000
So, I worked in the pharma space,

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:27.000
and this is really important because it allows us

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:30.000
to make decisions on our clinical trials faster

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
and get medicines to patients a little bit more quickly.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
But all of these principles are really applicable

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:37.000
across industries.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:40.000
And so, my hope is that you can take some of these ideas

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
from this talk and bring it back

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
and apply it to your own work.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:47.000
And if I have any time left,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
I guess I'll take some questions.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:51.000
Thank you.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:56.000
Okay, thank you, Kristen.

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.000
Really interesting to see what you've built

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
along with your team.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
So, we do have time for a few questions.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:02.000
Okay, great.

00:18:02.000 --> 00:18:04.000
So, the first one is from Marlene,

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
and they ask, Kristen,

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:09.000
how does this process deal with file versioning

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
and data edits slash changes?

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
Is the entire file removed and reloaded?

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
So, if a file is changed?

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
File versioning and data edits.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:23.000
Oh, yes.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
So, we do get new,

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
like the process is designed to handle new files.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So, we'll get one file.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
It will generate an output off of that file.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.000
As we get like a new copy,

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:32.000
it will redo the process,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
and then it will find issues in that file,

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
and then it will save a new output.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
Typically, we're working with cumulative data,

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
so we'll have the same data,

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
and then new data just gets added.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
But occasionally, the data does change,

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:45.000
and so the output will kind of detect that, too.

00:18:47.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Okay, we have time for another question.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:51.000
So, this is from Anonymous.

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
Why isn't the package open to the public?

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Are there plans to make a public version?

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.000
Well, we're not sure.

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
So, we just started sharing it externally

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:01.000
with other groups in Pfizer,

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:03.000
so we'll see where we go from there.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
Okay, and one more question.

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:08.000
Can other validation packages,

00:19:08.000 --> 00:19:09.000
like point blank,

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
be used for quality control?

00:19:12.000 --> 00:19:14.000
I think it's a different type of quality control.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:16.000
So, we're trying to really, like,

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:17.000
we want to ensure things are correct,

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:19.000
but we don't actually want to over-QC.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:21.000
So, we want to find, like,

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:23.000
what is really the necessary parts

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
that need to be correct in order for analysis,

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.000
because we don't want to exclude samples,

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.000
because we're working with patient data,

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:30.000
and so we don't want to say, like,

00:19:30.000 --> 00:19:31.000
oh, this patient provided the sample,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
but there's something minor wrong with it,

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:34.000
and so we're not going to use it.

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:37.000
So, we really do want to kind of keep our QC

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:39.000
to what's exactly essential.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:41.000
Okay, thank you so much.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
That's all the time we have for questions,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.000
but another round of applause for Kristen.

00:19:45.000 --> 00:19:46.000
Thank you.

